<br>
Did they really think that people wouldn't look at all these items across the board, and view them as a reflection of what to expect in the next batch?<br>
<br>
Brienna says &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The focus items we've seen so far are a nice start. If people would relax and give them a chance I'm sure we'll see more in a future patch.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
That's exactly what I'm talking about. If what we got in the last round is any indication of what we can expect in the next round (as has traditionally been the case when it comes to Verant implementing things over multiple patches), it's no wonder people are crying foul before waiting for the epilogue.<br>
<br>
Miss Foxfyre says &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Whatever. Don't let one issue get in the way of the larger picture. The fat lady hasn't sung yet. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
I know you're trying to be optimistic, and maybe trying to give VI some benefit of the doubt. But admit it... you can't help but think that Verant is going to show the same lack of attention and forethought to the higher-tier items as they did with the first batch.<br>
<br>
1. For some of the existing items, it's as if someone in VI's dev department threw darts at a chart to determine which focus effect to apply to each item. <br>
2. VI tossed Risk vs. Reward out the window, by not taking into account the difficulty of personally obtaining each item; they assumed too heavily that players can all afford to &quot;buy up&quot; for items their characters are too low to obtain.<br>
3. They are not just encouraging twinking anymore, now they're requiring it for player casters to be balanced relative to their levels (I guess new players who don't have high level mains weren't considered at all).<br>
3. In the same patch, they improved caster NPCs exponentially more than they improved caster PCs.<br>
<br>
We aren't reading between the lines here. To use the book analogy -- we're simply looking at the first couple of chapters and wondering how in the world this thing got all the way to press with mistakes in punctuation, grammar, spelling....<br>
<br>
